Chess Piece Classifier¶

Chris Sorenson¶

08/06/2021¶

Goal: Create a chess piece classifier. Takes cropped images of single pieces and classifies the color and type of piece¶

Loading the Data¶

We've taken and cropped images of all 12 pieces and "empty" squares

We'll augment the (relatively small) dataset with rotation, sheer, and vertical split

In [7]:
images_folder = "CroppedImages"
img_height, img_width = 300, 180
batch_size = 16
targ_height = 100
targ_width = 90

# Data Generator with augmentation and scaling
data_gen = ImageDataGenerator(
    rescale=1./255,
    rotation_range=20,
    shear_range = .2,
    horizontal_flip=True,
    validation_split=0.3
)

# The Training Data
training_gen = data_gen.flow_from_directory(
    images_folder,
    target_size = (targ_height, targ_width),
    batch_size=batch_size,
    subset="training"
)

# The Validation Data
validation_gen = data_gen.flow_from_directory(
    images_folder,
    shuffle=False,
    target_size = (targ_height, targ_width),
    batch_size=batch_size,
    subset="validation"
)

Note that 'empty' squares can still have bits of pieces in them if the neighboring square is populated.

I don't have enough training data - but it's a pain to make more data so here we are.

Building our Classifier¶

Chess pieces (of a given color) look pretty similar.

Pieces have generally similar shapes, especially when considering that images are taken from slightly different angles. A picture of a king taken from a steep angle is very similar to a picture of a short pawn taken from a shallow angle.

Really only the 'head' of the piece is useful for identifying. So even though the input images are sized to 100x90, we need o extract as much detail as possible from the ~20x20 region with the piece's head. Our important feature is small, but very detailed.

To this end - our strategy is to stack a lot of convolution layers at the beginning, before any pooling occurs. Once pooling starts - and the fine detail of the piece head is lost - we pool very aggressively.

I tinkered with different classifiers - this is the best I managed

In [8]:
model = keras.models.Sequential()
    
# We start with many convolutions in a row
model.add(layers.Conv2D(128, 5, activation='relu', input_shape=(targ_height, targ_width, 3)))
model.add(layers.Conv2D(140, 3, activation='relu'))
model.add(layers.Conv2D(150, 3, activation='relu'))
model.add(layers.Conv2D(160, 3, activation='relu'))
model.add(layers.Conv2D(170, 3, activation='relu'))
model.add(layers.Conv2D(180, 3, activation='relu'))
model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D(3))

model.add(layers.Conv2D(256, 3, activation='relu'))
model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D(3))

model.add(layers.Flatten())
model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())

model.add(layers.Dense(200, activation='relu', activity_regularizer=regularizers.l2(1e-5)))
model.add(layers.Dropout(.4))

model.add(layers.Dense(100, activation='relu', activity_regularizer=regularizers.l2(1e-5)))
model.add(layers.Dropout(.4))

# Output
model.add(layers.Dense(13, activation='softmax'))

model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy',
              optimizer="adam",
              metrics=['acc'])

model.summary()

model = keras.models.load_model("ThirdAttempt")
model.summary()
evalu = model.evaluate(validation_gen)
results = model.predict(validation_gen)

predictions = list()
for i in range(len(validation_gen.labels)):
    predictions.append(results[i].tolist().index(max(results[i])))
labels = list(validation_gen.class_indices.keys())
cm = confusion_matrix(validation_gen.labels, predictions)
df_cm = pd.DataFrame(cm, index=labels, columns=labels)
df_cm

The classifier has a 81% accuracy overall on the testing data. However most of the errors fall into a few main categories. The confusion matrix is very telling:

  • It never miscategorizes a pieces color!
  • It easily confuses Kings and Queens. Unsurprising, given that they are both tall pieces, with almost identical bodies and a very minor differentiation in the 'crown'
  • It does very well identifying empty squares.
